The biology of Kampimodromus aberrans (Oudemans), a predator of the big bud 
mite, Phytoptus avellanae Nalepa, was studied under laboratory conditions. All 
experiments were conducted on hazelnut leaf discs in an incubator at 25 +/- 1 
degrees C, with 16:8 h L:D, at an average daily relative air humidity of 76%. 
Observations were made twice daily for the immature stages and daily for the 
adults to determine developmental time, survival and fecundity. The mean 
developmental time for females was 6.90 days and for males was 7.10 days, and 
mean adult longevity for females was 11.67 days. The mean total and daily egg 
production were 12.67 and 1.85 eggs, respectively. The net reproduction rate 
(R0) was 7.09 females/female, intrinsic rate of increase (rm) was 0.153 
female/female/day and mean generation time (T0) was 12.80 days. The mortality 
rate of immature stages was 0.66% and the sex ratio was 0.51 female.

